Body: 72. Extracting plan options from a telecom website
result:
```python
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

# Send a request to the telecom website
url = 'https://example-telecom-website.com/plans'
response = requests.get(url)

# Parse the HTML content using BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

# Find the section containing the plan options
plan_section = soup.find('div', class_='plan-options')

# Extract individual plans
plans = plan_section.find_all('div', class_='plan')

# Loop through each plan and extract relevant details
for plan in plans:
    plan_name = plan.find('h2').text.strip()
    plan_price = plan.find('span', class_='price').text.strip()
    plan_features = [feature.text.strip() for feature in plan.find_all('li', class_='feature')]
    
    print(f"Plan Name: {plan_name}")
    print(f"Price: {plan_price}")
    print("Features:")
    for feature in plan_features:
        print(f" - {feature}")
    print()
```

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

# URL of the website containing podcast episode lists
url = 'http://example.com/podcast'

# Send a GET request to the website
response = requests.get(url)

# Parse the HTML content using BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

# Find the container that holds the podcast episodes
# Update the selector to match the structure of the target website
episode_container = soup.find('div', class_='episode-list')

# Extract individual episodes from the container
episodes = episode_container.find_all('div', class_='episode')

# Iterate through the episodes and collect details
episode_list = []
for episode in episodes:
    title = episode.find('h2', class_='episode-title').text.strip()
    date = episode.find('span', class_='episode-date').text.strip()
    description = episode.find('p', class_='episode-description').text.strip()
    episode_list.append({
        'title': title,
        'date': date,
        'description': description
    })

# Print the collected episode details
for ep in episode_list:
    print(f"Title: {ep['title']}")
    print(f"Date: {ep['date']}")
    print(f"Description: {ep['description']}\n")
```

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

# Define the URL and headers to be used for the web request
url = 'https://exampleforum.com/popular-posts'  # replace with the target forum URL
headers = {'User-Agent': 'Mozilla/5.0'}

# Make a GET request to fetch the forum page content
response = requests.get(url, headers=headers)
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

# Initialize an empty list to store posts information
posts = []

# Loop through each post found on the forum page
for post in soup.find_all(class_='post-class'):  # replace with the appropriate class or tag
    # Extract and handle information about each post (title, link, and date)
    title_element = post.find(class_='title-class')  # replace with the appropriate class or tag
    link_element = post.find('a')['href']
    date_element = post.find(class_='date-class')  # replace with the appropriate class or tag

    # Safely retrieve text from elements, including fallback for missing data
    title = title_element.get_text() if title_element else 'No title'
    link = link_element if link_element else 'No link'
    date = date_element.get_text() if date_element else 'No date'

    # Append the extracted post information to the list
    posts.append({
        'title': title,
        'link': link,
        'date': date
    })

# Print out all collected posts information
for post in posts:
    print(post)
```

6. Append the extracted information of each post to the list.
7. Print out the collected information of all posts.

def parse_footer_contact_info(url):
    response = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

    # Searching for footer element
    footer = soup.find('footer')

        # Extracting email addresses

    return contact_info

import requests

# Send a request to the telecom website
url = 'https://example-telecom-website.com/plans'
response = requests.get(url)

soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')

plan_section = soup.find('div', class_='plan-options')

# Extract individual plans
plans = plan_section.find_all('div', class_='plan')

    print(f"Plan Name: {plan_name}")
    print(f"Price: {plan_price}")
    print("Features:")
    for feature in plan_features:
        print(f" - {feature}")
    print()

import requests

def get_html_content(url):

    return response.content

def parse_editorial_lists(url):
    html_content = get_html_content(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(html_content, 'html.parser')

    # Assuming editorial items are within a specific div class, e.g., 'editorial-item'
    editorial_items = soup.find_all('div', class_='editorial-item')

        summary = item.find('p').get_text() if item.find('p') else ""
        author = item.find('span', class_='author').get_text() if item.find('span', class_='author') else ""

            'title': title,
            'summary': summary,
            'author': author
        })

    return editorial_list

# Example usage

import requests

episode_container = soup.find('div', class_='episode-list')

    date = episode.find('span', class_='episode-date').text.strip()

        'title': title,
        'date': date,
        'description': description
    })

# Print the collected episode details

    print(f"Title: {ep['title']}")
    print(f"Date: {ep['date']}")
    print(f"Description: {ep['description']}\n")

import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

def get_song_lyrics(url):
    # Send an HTTP GET request to the specified URL and handle the response.
    response = requests.get(url)
    if response.status_code != 200:
        return "Failed to retrieve the webpage."
    
    # Parse the HTML content of the response with BeautifulSoup.
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')
    
    # Try to find the lyrics in a specific div with class 'lyrics'.
    lyrics_div = soup.find('div', {'class': 'lyrics'})
    if lyrics_div:
        return lyrics_div.get_text(strip=True)
    
    # If the lyrics are not found in a div with class 'lyrics', gather all paragraphs that have 'lyrics' in their class attributes.
    lyrics_paragraphs = soup.find_all('p')
    lyrics = []
    for para in lyrics_paragraphs:
        if 'class' in para.attrs and 'lyrics' in para['class']:
            lyrics.append(para.get_text(strip=True))
    
    # Combine all gathered lyrics paragraphs into a single string, separated by newlines.
    return "\n".join(lyrics)

Body: 40. Extracting exchange rates from a financial site
result:
```python
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

# URL of the financial site to scrape exchange rates from
url = "https://www.example-financial-site.com/exchange-rates"

# Send a request to fetch the HTML content of the page
response = requests.get(url)
html_content = response.content

# Parse the HTML content using BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup(html_content, 'html.parser')

# Find the specific table or section containing the exchange rates
exchange_table = soup.find('table', {'id': 'exchange-rates-table'})

# Extract exchange rates
exchange_rates = {}
for row in exchange_table.find_all('tr')[1:]:  # skipping the header row
    cells = row.find_all('td')
    currency = cells[0].text.strip()
    rate = cells[1].text.strip()
    exchange_rates[currency] = rate

# Print the extracted exchange rates
for currency, rate in exchange_rates.items():
    print(f"{currency}: {rate}")
```
